JOHANNESBURG - #FeesMustFall activist Mcebo Dlamini said he has mixed feelings about his sentencing. Dlamini has been found guilty of public violence and given a suspended sentence of two-and-a-half years. READ: Student activist Mcebo Dlamini ready to lead ANCYL Dlamini was arrested in 2016 during protests for free higher education. He said a criminal record will curb some of his future plans, but he is glad the case has finally been concluded. Dlamini said he would be appealing to President Cyril Ramaphosa and the Justice Department for either a presidential pardon or an expungement of his criminal record in order to practice law.